"{\n  \"text\": \"Hi everybody, Scotty here. Gonna give a quick garden tour. It's Houston, Texas fall time weather. Um, we're getting towards the winter, it's uh the beginning of December, uh, but still very temperate here as it will stay all winter long. Uh the first thing I want to do when talking about my garden is my compost pile. Uh if y'all know anything or seen any of my videos, I'm obsessed with composting and uh the carbon in my soil. So this is my compost pile. It's about thigh high. Good ten time pitch fork to pitch it with. About uh eight, nine feet wide, about six feet long or whatever. Um most of the heat is gone out of this. It's about in its third week, and I'm only pitching this stuff about once uh every week, but that's plenty. And uh truthfully, it's it's lost most of its heat. Uh there's a little bit left in there, and I will put that into the worm pile here shortly and start up a new pile. And let's go to that worm pile and take a look at these. Okay, this is my worm pile. Uh this is where the compost finishes off. It's over in the corner of my yard. And I have I just watered it because at the end of the summer, and we've just only recently gotten over this and even uh it's been real dry, and that's Houston every late summer or early fall. Um, but uh the soil is gorgeous. This is good stuff, it's real woody. All this uh the big particles like the big sticks will magically rise to the top as the rain kind of drops the particles down and all filters through the big stuff comes up, and you just scrape that off uh before you are you know I'll do it like two, three times through uh throughout the uh curing season, which will be about two, three months. I'll add stuff to this for another probably till the end of December, and then I'll I'll let it go and not add anything else so it can completely cure before we put it in the soil. That'll be about two, three months. It'll be ready for spring. Alright, this is uh uh the older part of my worm pile, and I'm gonna give you a little sample of what this looks like. This is called an aggregate. So once we're done uh with composting, there's no life left in this soil or in that soil, in the compost soil. Thermophilic bacteria break down the matter and they run everything else out. It gets up to like 130, 140, even more uh temperature-wise in there, uh, and consequently everything runs from it. There's no life in it once a thermophilic bacteria, I mean theoretically, uh no life in it. Once the thermophilic bacteria are finished breaking down everything and they've cleared out, it's kind of empty soil. So what we do is we cure it, and what we're this will be full of uh well, maybe not today, but because it's been so dry. But if you look, this stuff just falls apart, but it holds it kind of it holds its structure. These are very loose bonds, these are called aggregates, and this is basically worm and microbe uh poo, saliva and stuff, and uh it's just uh this is all being held together by real active organic matter. Um, as that matter dies, or that all that life in there dies, this will go uh much more crumbly and just break apart and turn into dust. But while it's being held together like that, you can really tell it's full of life. And just to this is generally full of wormholes, and there's one right there just to kind of show you. These things have been pilf uh perforated with worm. And you can see all their marks. Now, after several months, and this is the part that I just used for fall, and that's just a little corner of it that I didn't use, uh, didn't get around to using every bit of it, as you never do. Um, and so I want to show you what a good living aggregate is, what it looks like when it goes into the garden. I'll break all those up like I just did and put them in the garden. That'll be the last time I break up my aggregates. I want aggregates bad that holds the water in. See, aggregates aren't strong enough for the roots uh to easily I mean the roots easily penetrate because they're weak, but they're strong enough to hold the water. Uh they're strong enough not to break the hydrogen bonds or to break the hydrogen bonds in water and disperse the water and hold the water, and that's the whole key to soil structure is it holds more water. You never have to water it. Yes, the microbes, you know, the nutrient uptake, all this and that, but at the end of the day, boy, when you only water your garden after it hasn't rained for two weeks, you're really killing it. Anyway, let's go take a look at the garden. Okay, so I'm uh doing a new system of trellising in my garden. It's just a simple pole with some strings on it, and I'm going straight up. In the past, I had all this extensive trellis system that would carry the the cucumber vines over and up and you know, create like a whole area that was covered, and my soil kind of suffered from it. It didn't get enough light to grow anything, and that's not what I'm looking to do. So I'll hold back the cucumber growth a little bit. Also, it's really hard to harvest because cucumbers would get on the wrong side of the fence on me. Anyway, so I'm just doing these strings, and they'll be growing straight up, and consequently, I'll have a lot more growth on the lower parts of my soil. And you can see that uh here, let me hop over this little chicken fence because the chickens want to get into my garden bad. Uh so down here you can see that I have a very living soil. This is just ryegrass, and there's all sorts of fetch and legumes in there. Uh I have lots of cover crops working, and but I also have like this is a turnip. This is these are uh this is a turnip. These are my uh multiplier onions, and those are great green onions. I eat a lot of those. That's a cucumber. Um cucumbers do not do as well down here in fall as they do in spring. Um but over here, you'll see I have lots of lettuces. Ooh, these are carrots that I have. Lots of roots and lettuces and things going. But I also have a pretty healthy cover crop going in there. I think for spring I'll hold back on all the extra stuff and just focus on more production crops. But I really wanted to work on getting my fall cover crop real hearty of uh getting this, and you can really see a good one right here. This is a very living bed. It's got everything in the world in, and that's kind of what you're looking to do, or I'm looking to do. Create a lot of diversity. That improves your soil. Right there. Look at that. That's a great big old sunflower. I'm gonna take the seeds off that when it crop, when it uh finally flowers. But over here I got a bunch of uh trellises that I put up, or not trellis, but like a big cage I put up. There's chicken wire covering this, and it goes all around it because I had squirrels uh come and eat all my eggplant. It really upset me because I just learned how to make babbo ganoosh. It was really good. I was smoking the eggplant and then all of a sudden I had none. And I mean, just they were pilfering my eggplant. So I built a giant cage just to keep squirrels and birds out. And hopefully uh come spring that will do me a lot of favors when I'm trying to get my tomatoes to turn red on vine, on the vine, which they've I've never been able to do because as soon as they turn red, the birds just have them. And so like I've created these big cages to protect myself from that, and it was super easy. These blocks that I use, they have little areas where tubies go in them. So you can put your boards down and then you can put all sorts of things in them and tie them all together and just basically dumb little wall formation that I made. Super easy. I didn't spend any, I just cut a bunch of two by fours in half uh to to do all that, and it turned out real well. I'm real happy with it. Um but yeah, that's that's my garden right now. I'm real excited about it. I can't wait to get the spring crop in uh and to harvest the fall crop. Anyway, thanks y'all.\",\n  \"sentences\": [\n    {\n     